-- Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Mexico: Latin America Bond and Currency Preview
-- Andrea Jaramillo
-- 2010-04-07T04:00:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-04-06/brazil-chile-colombia-mexico-latin-america-bond-and-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Latin American local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous day’s session.  
 Brazil: Manufacturers increased the use of installed
capacity to 81.7 percent in February from 81.4 percent the
previous month, according to the median estimate of 10 analysts
surveyed by Bloomberg News. The National Industrial
Confederation is set to release the report at 9 a.m. New York
time.  
 The real gained 0.5 percent to 1.7531 per U.S. dollar.  
 The yield on the zero-coupon, real-denominated bond due in
January 2011 rose four basis points, or 0.04 percentage point,
to 10.44 percent, according to Bloomberg prices.  
 Chile: The nation’s trade surplus widened to $1.45 billion
in March from $1.33 billion a month earlier, according to the
median estimate of 16 economists in a Bloomberg News survey. The
central bank is slated to release the monthly trade report at
8:30 a.m. New York time.  
 The peso fell 0.2 percent to 520.18 per dollar.  
 The yield for a basket of Chile’s 10-year peso bonds in
inflation-linked currency units, called unidades de fomento,
fell three basis points to 3.11 percent, according to Bloomberg
composite prices.  
 Colombia: The peso weakened 0.3 percent to 1,915.18 per
dollar.  
 The yield on Colombia’s benchmark 11 percent bonds due July
2020 fell 13 basis points to 8.64 percent, according to
Colombia’s stock exchange.  
 Other prices in Latin American markets:  
 Argentina: The peso was little changed at 3.8799 per
dollar.  
 Mexico: The peso strengthened 0.3 percent to 12.2178 per
dollar.  
 The yield on Mexico’s 10 percent bond due December 2024
rose one basis point to 7.92 percent, according to Banco
Santander SA.  
 Peru: The sol closed was little changed at 2.8375 per
dollar.  
 The yield on Peru’s 8.6 percent bond maturing August 2017
was little changed at 5.09 percent, according to Citigroup
Inc.’s unit in Lima.  
